05059nam a22008775i 9783110730548DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021937868  a97831107305487 a10.1515/97831107305482doi  a(DE-B1597)573659  a(OCoLC)1257324157  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBD171b.C66 2021 7aPHI0040002bisacsh04a121.52231 aConstantin, Jan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEpistemic Defeat :bA Treatment of Defeat as an Independent Phenomenon /cJan Constantin. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (X, 287 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEpistemic Studies : Philosophy of Science, Cognition and Mind ,x2512-5168 ;v4700tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 Defeaters, Functional Profiles and Deep Distinctions -- t2 Rebutting Defeat -- t3 Undercutting Defeat -- t4 Putting Things Together -- t5 Defeat and Epistemic Justification -- t6 Defeat and Disagreement -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex – Definitions and Examples -- tIndex – Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA number of well-developed theories shed light on the question, under what circumstances our beliefs enjoy epistemic justification. Yet, comparatively little is known about epistemic defeat—when new information causes the loss of epistemic justification. This book proposes and defends a detailed account of epistemic defeaters. The main kinds of defeaters are analyzed in detail and integrated into a general framework that aims to explain how beliefs lose justification. It is argued that defeaters introduce incompatibilities into a noetic system and thereby prompt a structured re-evaluation process that makes a justified reinstatement of the defeated belief impossible. The account is then applied to the topic of disagreement, where it is used in an argument for conciliationism, as well as a new explanation for higher-order defeat. Throughout the book, the notion of defeat is the center of attention, while a number of new issues are discussed at the intersections of defeat and justification. Specifically, new problems are raised for broadly internalist accounts of defeat, a fully descriptive reliabilist account of defeat is provided, and the case for normative defeat is revisited.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBelief and doubt. 0aError. 4aUneinigkeit. 4aepistemische Niederlage. 4aepistemische Rechtfertigung. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh  aEpistemic defeat.  adisagreement.  aepistemic justification.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2021 Englishz978311075415508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2021z9783110753929oZDB-23-DPH0 cEPUBz97831107306850 cprintz978311073535240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311073054840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110730548423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110730548/original  a978-3-11-075070-6  DG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1b2021  a978-3-11-075072-0  DG Ebook Package English 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075415-5  EBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_E